        <label for="depthSlider">Recursion Depth: <span id="depthValue">1</span></label>
        <input type="range" id="depthSlider" min="1" max="12" value="1">
    </div>

    <div id="explanation">
        <h2>Explanation of Recursion in Fractal Trees</h2>
        <p>This visualization draws a fractal tree using recursion, where each branch splits into smaller sub-branches until a base case is reached. The recursion depth, controlled by the slider, determines how many levels of branches are drawn (from 1 to 12).</p>

        <h3>Recursion Depth Limits</h3>
        <p>Recursion depth refers to the number of times a function calls itself. In this example, the tree's complexity grows exponentially with depth: a depth of 1 draws a simple trunk, while a depth of 12 creates a highly detailed tree. However, most programming environments have a limit on recursion depth due to memory constraints, typically around 10,000–100,000 calls in JavaScript, depending on the browser and system resources.</p>

        <h3>Stack Overflow Risks</h3>
        <p>Each recursive call adds a new frame to the program's call stack, which stores local variables and execution context. If the recursion depth exceeds the stack's capacity (e.g., due to very deep calls), it can cause a "stack overflow" error. In this demo, we've limited the slider to a maximum of 12 to avoid this, but in real-world scenarios, depths beyond 15–20 could crash the program, especially in resource-constrained environments like mobile browsers.</p>

        <h3>Practical Solutions</h3>
        <p>To mitigate stack overflow risks, recursion can be converted to an iterative approach. For instance, instead of using recursive function calls, you could use a loop with a stack data structure (e.g., an array) to simulate the recursion. This "explicit stack" method processes each level iteratively, avoiding the call stack's limitations and being more memory-efficient for deep structures. In JavaScript, this might involve a while loop that pushes and pops branch parameters onto an array until no more levels remain. Iterative methods are particularly useful for large-scale fractals or performance-critical applications.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Get references to the canvas and slider elements
        const canvas = document.getElementById('treeCanvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        const slider = document.getElementById('depthSlider');
        const depthValueSpan = document.getElementById('depthValue');

        // Function to draw the fractal tree recursively
        function drawTree(x1, y1, length, angle, depth) {
            if (depth === 0) return;  // Base case: Stop recursion when depth reaches 0

            // Calculate the end point of the current branch
            const x2 = x1 + length * Math.cos(angle * Math.PI / 180);  // Convert angle to radians
            const y2 = y1 + length * Math.sin(angle * Math.PI / 180);  // Note: Canvas y-axis increases downwards

            // Draw the line for the current branch
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(x1, y1);
            ctx.lineTo(x2, y2);
            ctx.strokeStyle = 'green';  // Set color for the branches
            ctx.lineWidth = depth * 0.5;  // Make lines thicker for deeper levels
            ctx.stroke();

            // Recursive calls for the left and right branches
            const newLength = length * 0.7;  // Reduce length for sub-branches
            const branchAngle = 30;  // Angle for branches (adjust as needed)
            drawTree(x2, y2, newLength, angle - branchAngle, depth - 1);  // Left branch
            drawTree(x2, y2, newLength, angle + branchAngle, depth - 1);  // Right branch
        }

        // Function to redraw the tree based on the slider value
        function redraw() {
            const depth = parseInt(slider.value);  // Get the current depth from the slider
            depthValueSpan.textContent = depth;  // Update the displayed depth value

            // Clear the canvas
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

            // Set initial parameters for the tree
            const startX = canvas.width / 2;  // Start at the center horizontally
            const startY = canvas.height;     // Start at the bottom
            const initialLength = 100;       // Initial branch length
            const initialAngle = -90;        // Initial angle (pointing upwards)

            // Draw the tree with the current depth
            drawTree(startX, startY, initialLength, initialAngle, depth);
        }

        // Add event listener to the slider
        slider.addEventListener('input', redraw);

        // Initial draw when the page loads
        redraw();
    </script>
